Today’s caveat: behaviour adjustment.

Influenza vaccination in the United Kingdom

Joint work between Analytica Laser and Astrazeneca 2014-2016

  • A retrospective observational analysis of post-pandemic influenza-related outcomes in the United Kingdom, 2010–2014
  • Impact of increased influenza vaccination in 2–3-year-old children on disease burden within the general population: A Bayesian model-based approach

Influenza vaccination in the United Kingdom: background

  • Influenza burden: deaths, hospitalisations, number of illnesses
    • Can extend to economic cost
  • Starting in 2013 the vaccination policy in the UK has been changed to not only include the elderly (most at risk), but also young children
  • Consensus: on average, such policy leads to a reduction in flu infections
  • However, influenza epidemics are highly variable season-to-season
    • properties of the virus,
      • levels of susceptbiility in the population,
      • vaccine efficacy

How to estimate effect in a given season?

Role of modeling in vaccination policy

  • Research question: For a given season, what would be influenza burden if an alternative vaccination policy was in place?

  • Counterfactual framing: compare world with/without vaccine in children

  • Solution 1: pilot study RCT

    • trustworthy
    • setting-specific
    • expensive (large sample) and slow
    • requires careful design (epidemiological spillovers!)

  • Solution 2: modeling (simulated potential outcomes)

    • generalisable
    • fast and cheap
    • all models are wrong!
    • hard to validate

Observational data

  • In a retrospective, observational study we collected data (healthcare records for 7% of population in England) from four influenza seasons 2010-2014
    • Doctor visits (grouped based on doctor’s diagnosis),
    • Laboratory testing
    • Hospitalisations and deaths
    • Vaccinations

Observational data: pyramid of surveillance

No data = assumptions from other sources needed.

Constructing likelihood

Let us look at Figure 3 in Rajaram et al.

  • Vaccination rates are data
  • Outcomes observed across four datasets (CPRD, RCGP, HES link, ONS link)
  • Behaviour, vaccine efficacy are constant
  • Susceptibility, properties of virus are parameters (stochastic)
  • Sensitivity and specificity of diagnoses are also parameters (stochastic)

Mechanistic model of vaccination

Bayesian model: summary

  • Model of infection rates in the UK population was a deterministic SEEIIR model (a large number of linear ODEs), for four different influenza strains
    • Parameters: virus properties, susceptibility of different groups
  • A likelihood model linked the outcomes (visits, hospitalisations, deaths) to influenza infections
    • Parameters: probabilities of events conditional on influenza infection
  • Most parameters were given informative priors, elicited from experts and literature search on influenza
    • Many parameters were also age-specific
  • Markov chain Monte Carlo algorithm was used for inference
    • Parts programmed in C++ for speed
    • Long runs needed due to correlation in parameters and large parameter space

Short tangent: Bayesian statistics recap

Bayesian statistics offers a way of making statements about probability, about statistical parameters \(\theta\) (or unobserved data), conditional on observed data \(y\).

  • Step 1: hypothesise a model (joint probability for \(\theta\) and \(y\))

    • \(p(\theta, y) = p(y | \theta)p(\theta)\)

  • Step 2: condition unobserved quantities on observed data

    • \(p(\theta | y) = \frac{p(\theta)p(y | \theta)}{p(y)}\)
    • \(p(y)\) is a summation over all possible values of \(\theta\) (considered a constant and omitted)

  • Step 3: criticise the model

    • How well does the model fit data?
    • How does the result depend on assumptions of step 1?
    • Are the conclusions of the result reasonable?

Short tangent: why go Bayesian?

  • Bayesian inference matches common-sense intuitions about meaning of probability, uncertainty and intervals
  • Overcomes deficiencies in data (inference on small samples, informative priors)
  • Propagates uncertainty
  • Avoids problems of Fisher/Neyman-Pearson null hypothesis significance testing (as practiced)

Result

According to our model (Rajaram et al, 2017):

  • Vaccinating additional 1-2% of population (targetting children aged 2-3 and primary school age) could result in 6-10% reduction in overall influenza rates
  • The infection rates decreased across all age groups, which led to similar reductions in hospitalisations (infants and elderly) and deaths (elderly)
  • The inferred reduction was variable across seasons and uncertain

Capturing uncertainty

Approaches to capturing uncertainty:

  • Simple: best vs worst case scenario
  • Complicated: Monte Carlo draws over all assumptions
    • How to partition variability vs uncertainty?
    • Depending on the context you will want to set one/both to 0

Example from an ongoing project: just for visual flavour. Coloured points are estimates of flu burden, over ~10 seasons.

Other flu modeling work on this

Check out the links in electronic version of the slides

  • Baguelin et al. is the original study that outlines Bayesian approach
  • Backer et al. show how over lifetime the mean risk will decrease, but between-season variation will increase
  • Kassianos et al. discuss evidence over 6 seasons of the UK programme.
  • Weidermann et al. apply SEIR-type modeling to German context and find smaller than expected impacts

A lot of COVID modeling work uses similar approaches

Agent-based models used to inform policy from the start, but inference on parameters done using populational models.

  • Bayesian approaches to viral parameters
    • Verity et al. estimated time to symptons and IFRs; see in particular Fig 1-3
  • Bayesian SEIR inference
    • Example from very early on in the pandemic: Hauser et al.
    • New approaches computationally feasible but required a lot of optimisation
  • “DGP”-like Bayesian approach (Imperial College):
    • Vollmer et al.
    • Flaxman et al.
    • R package epidemia
  • More Bayesian modeling of NPIs: Brauner et al. in Science, Sharma et al. in Nature, CMMID (LSHTM) in BMC Medicine

Should we trust this (or any) result?

  • How bad is our code?
    • UK: debate over Ferguson et al. Imperial College model (used for 15+ years?)
  • Variability in virus parameters accounted for?
    • Important to remember this for prediction/decision models
  • What happens over longer time-span (viral evolution, loss of immunity later in life)?
    • There is no eradication strategy for flu (or COVID)
    • see the Backer et al. paper cited earlier
  • Uncertainty in takeup of an intervention (vaccination, NPI, therapeutic)
    • In the case of flu there were no issues
    • For COVID there is some research; see Brouard et al for some France-specific notes
  • Behaviour adjustment (next slide)

Behavioural adjustment issues

Also called individual/voluntary behaviour change. A lot of debate between epidemiologists and economists. (Some of it not very nice!)

  • Gans discusses this as an economist
    • worth checking out Voxeu summary of his points (and other articles)
  • Atkeson has a more complex model and an empirical result about pandemic fatigue
  • math epi modeling solution (?) is via changing contact matrices, see e.g. Prem et al.
    • There is probably much better empirical result than this, just an example

We shouldn’t trust these either—but any model without behaviour adjustment cannot claim to predict impact of policy.
